item.title: China's Xi Moves to Tighten Grip on Hong Kong With New Laws
item.description: With his plan to impose sweeping antisedition legislation on Hong Kong, Chinese leader Xi Jinping has revealed a willingness to alter the onetime British colony’s special status as a self-governing city with a speed and scope that has surprised many.

item.title: Crash Probe to Assess if Pakistani Airliner Dragged Engines on Runway in Landing Attempt
item.description: The investigation into Friday’s deadly crash in Karachi will examine whether the jet’s engines were damaged in an aborted first landing, causing a loss of power when the plane circled around for a second attempt.

item.title: Netanyahu Goes on Offensive Day After His Corruption Trial Opens
item.description: A day after he appeared in court on corruption charges, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu maintained a fiery public defense that risked deepening divisions in Israel’s fractured politics.

item.title: Poor Countries Weigh Easing Lockdowns With Rising Coronavirus Cases
item.description: Many developing countries are easing restrictions, saying they cause too much economic pain, while new infections and deaths are growing.

item.title: Bert Hewitt Was Dying of Coronavirus in Bhutan. Then His Family Asked for U.S. Help.
item.description: Repatriations of Americans stranded abroad following abrupt border closings from the coronavirus have topped 90,000, and the number is still rising. The evacuation of Bert Hewitt from the mountains of Bhutan highlights the extent of the State Department’s program to bring Americans caught in precarious circumstances home.

item.title: Wuhan Tests Nine Million People for Coronavirus in 10 Days
item.description: The Chinese city at the initial center of the pandemic said it had collected coronavirus swab tests from more than nine million people over the past 10 days, an ambitious response to the re-emergence of a handful of fresh cases earlier this month.
